### What's life with diabetes like now? And what could it be like in the
That’s what we wanted to find out. So we spent summer 2017 holding the UK’s
biggest conversation about diabetes. More than 9,000 people shared their
We heard what we need to do build a better future for people with diabetes.
Now we need your help to make it a reality.
## Join the fight for a better future
You told us that diabetes affects all aspects of someone’s life, and that
sometimes, things can be tough. And, you also told us that a lack of awareness
and understanding can lead to stigma, and people not getting the support they
But we also heard that there are steps we can and must take right now to build
a better future for people living with diabetes.
We put everything we learned into our Future of Diabetes report (PDF, 5.5MB).
> “We’ve come a long way in the past 20 years… compared to where we were, it’s
> bloody fantastic. So let’s preserve what’s brilliant… celebrate that we have
> made a lot of progress and expand upon that so more people can benefit.”
#### People with diabetes told us they want:
1. More support for emotional and psychological health
2. Better access to healthcare professionals who understand diabetes
5. More support and understanding at work and school
6. Hope for the future through diabetes research and prevention of Type 2 diabetes.
Download the full report (PDF, 5.5MB) to learn more about people’s hopes for
We want to see these changes happen. So, we’re calling for action from across
the health service and governments in all four UK nations to help make this
But we can’t do it alone. We need to work together to create a better future
for people living with diabetes, and we need action from governments, health
services, policy makers, healthcare professionals and local decision makers.
There are three different ways you can join the fight for a better future for
Thank you to everyone who took part in our Future of Diabetes big
conversations, survey and events, and shared their experiences with us. By
coming together to share knowledge and fight diabetes we can build a better
future – a world where diabetes can do no harm.
